<%# Phase 37 Wave A1 — `/channels` mocked shell.

    Locked layout (2026-05-19 user — chip-row consolidation pass):

      channels  [+][-]
      [ ] 7d  [ ] 28d  [ ] 3m  [ ] 365d  [ ] alltime  [ ] <prev_year>  [ ] <current_year>  [ ] <prev_month>  [ ] <current_month>       [ ]| | [ ]| | [ ]| |
      ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────  (hairline)
      <ID-card shelf — one tile per channel, horizontal scroll>

    Year/month chip values are computed by
    `Pito::Formatter::CurrentChannelFilterChips` so the chip set tracks
    today's date instead of hard-coded literals. URL values for the
    year chips are 4-digit year strings; month-chip URL values are the
    lowercase 3-letter abbreviation (`apr`, `may`, ...), display labels
    capitalize via `%b` (`Apr`, `May`, ...).

    Wave A1 ships with the generic `FilterChipComponent` for every
    chip — the controller doesn't yet read `?windows=`, `?calendar=`,
    or `?channels=`, so the chips toggle URL state harmlessly (same
    UX as /games chips). Live filtering wires up in later A-steps
    once the user signs off on the visuals.

    Mock data lives in `Channel::MockData`. %>

<% calendar_chips = Pito::Formatter::CurrentChannelFilterChips.call %>

<%= render(Channel::TitleBarComponent.new) %>

<%# Two-column block: LEFT = single chip row (time windows + dynamic
    year/month chips inline AFTER alltime); RIGHT = avatar shelf.

    Outer flex container baseline-aligns the two columns so the chip
    row and the RIGHT shelf's checkboxes share the same baseline.
    `gap: 16px` between left and right groups matches
    `Game::FilterRowComponent`'s outer left/right gap
    (filter_row_component.html.erb L18). %>
<section class="channels-chrome"
         style="display: flex; flex-wrap: wrap; gap: 16px; align-items: flex-start; justify-content: space-between; margin: 6px 0;">
  <div class="channels-chrome__filters"
       style="display: flex; flex-direction: column; gap: 6px;">
    <%# Single chip row — time windows + dynamic year/month chips
        appended after `alltime`. Window chips toggle `?windows=`;
        year+month chips toggle `?calendar=`. Both use csv multi-select. %>
    <div class="channels-filter-row"
         style="display: flex; flex-wrap: wrap; gap: 6px; align-items: baseline;">
      <% %w[7d 28d 3m 365d alltime].each do |window| %>
        <%= render(FilterChipComponent.new(
              label: window,
              param: "windows",
              value: window,
              current_params: request.query_parameters,
              csv: true,
              path: "/channels"
            )) %>
      <% end %>
      <% calendar_chips[:years].each do |chip| %>
        <%= render(FilterChipComponent.new(
              label: chip[:label],
              param: "calendar",
              value: chip[:value],
              current_params: request.query_parameters,
              csv: true,
              path: "/channels"
            )) %>
      <% end %>
      <% calendar_chips[:months].each do |chip| %>
        <%= render(FilterChipComponent.new(
              label: chip[:label],
              param: "calendar",
              value: chip[:value],
              current_params: request.query_parameters,
              csv: true,
              path: "/channels"
            )) %>
      <% end %>
    </div>
  </div>
  <div class="channels-chrome__avatars">
    <%= render(Channel::AvatarShelfComponent.new(channels: @channels, current_params: request.query_parameters)) %>
  </div>
</section>

<hr class="hairline">

<%# Wave A1 (2026-05-19 chip-row consolidation) main content area —
    first row is the ID-card shelf (6 cards, one per channel). Uses
    the canonical headless `ShelfComponent` (heading: nil) — the
    parallel `Channels::IdCardShelfComponent` was removed in the same
    pass. Subsequent A-steps fill the remaining metric sections
    (basics totals, top content, window summaries, audience, traffic,
    heatmap, trends) beneath it inside the same `.channels-main` wrapper.

    2026-05-19 — each shelf renders a trailing `<hr class="hairline">`
    so the bottom edge of the shelf reads as a clean separator, matching
    the inter-shelf hairline convention used on `/games` (see
    `app/views/games/index.html.erb` lines 158, 173, 180). The
    `ShelfComponent` does NOT emit its own `<hr>` by design (see the
    header comment on `app/components/shelf_component.rb`); views own
    the composition between shelves. %>
<section class="channels-main">
  <%= render(ShelfComponent.new(
        heading: nil,
        extra_classes: "channels-id-card-shelf",
        shelf_kind: "channels-id-cards"
      )) do %>
    <% @channels.each do |channel| %>
      <%= render(Channel::IdCardComponent.new(channel: channel)) %>
    <% end %>
  <% end %>
  <hr class="hairline">

  <%# Wave A2 — Basics section variant gallery (2026-05-19).

      Three variants of the Basics row render here so the user can pick
      which visual treatment lands as the canonical surface. After the
      user picks one, the other two components + their renders get
      removed in a follow-up dispatch.

      Each component emits its own trailing `<hr class="hairline">` so
      the variants are visually separated by the same inter-shelf
      hairline used above. %>

  <!-- variant 1: inline (compact `value label` pairs, 13px bold + 11px muted, 32px gap) -->
  <%= render(Channel::BasicsSectionInlineComponent.new(channels: @channels)) %>

  <!-- variant 2: card (bordered + tinted 4-cell grid, 22px bold value over 11px muted label) -->
  <%= render(Channel::BasicsSectionCardComponent.new(channels: @channels)) %>

  <!-- variant 3: separator (4-cell grid with vertical hairline rules, 22px bold value over 11px muted label) -->
  <%= render(Channel::BasicsSectionSeparatorComponent.new(channels: @channels)) %>

  <%# Top Content variant gallery (2026-05-19).

      Three variants of the union-merged top-videos list render here so
      the user can pick the visual treatment. After the user picks one,
      the other two components + their renders get removed in a follow-
      up dispatch.

      Source: `Channel::MockData.top_content`, filtered by the channel
      ids the page is rendering and sorted by `:views` desc. Components
      live in `app/components/channels/top_content_*_component.{rb,html.erb}`. %>

  <% selected_channel_ids = @channels.map { |c| c[:id] } %>
  <% top_videos = Channel::MockData.top_content
       .select { |v| selected_channel_ids.include?(v[:channel_id]) }
       .sort_by { |v| -v[:views].to_i } %>
  <% channel_name_map = Channel::MockData.channel_name_by_id %>

  <hr class="hairline">

  <!-- variant 1: vertical ranked list (rank + 80×45 thumb placeholder + title + views + channel badge per row) -->
  <%= render(Channel::TopContentListComponent.new(
        videos: top_videos,
        channel_name_by_id: channel_name_map
      )) %>

  <hr class="hairline">

  <!-- variant 2: 4-column tile grid (16:9 thumb placeholder + 2-line title + views + channel badge per tile) -->
  <%= render(Channel::TopContentGridComponent.new(
        videos: top_videos,
        channel_name_by_id: channel_name_map
      )) %>

  <hr class="hairline">

  <!-- variant 3: compact 3-column table (title | views | channel — most data-dense) -->
  <%= render(Channel::TopContentTableComponent.new(
        videos: top_videos,
        channel_name_by_id: channel_name_map
      )) %>

  <%# Device types section variant gallery (2026-05-19).

      Two variants of the device-type viewership breakdown render here
      so the user can pick the visual treatment. After the user picks
      one, the other component + its render gets removed in a follow-
      up dispatch.

      Aggregation across selected channels = view-count-weighted mean
      of each channel's device-type percentages, rounded + re-
      normalized to 100. Components live in
      `app/components/channels/device_types_*_component.{rb,html.erb}`. %>

  <!-- variant 1: donut (CSS conic-gradient with center label + bracketed legend) -->
  <%= render(Channel::DeviceTypesDonutComponent.new(channels: @channels)) %>

  <!-- variant 2: bars (horizontal bar list, one row per device) -->
  <%= render(Channel::DeviceTypesBarsComponent.new(channels: @channels)) %>

  <%# Window summaries section variant gallery (2026-05-19).

      Two variants of the per-window subs Δ / views Δ / hours Δ
      breakdown render here so the user can pick which lands as the
      canonical surface. After the user picks one, the other component
      + its render gets removed in a follow-up dispatch. %>

  <hr class="hairline">

  <!-- variant 1: tabs (5-tab strip with one active window's stat cards below; default = 28d) -->
  <%= render(Channel::WindowSummariesTabsComponent.new(channels: @channels)) %>

  <hr class="hairline">

  <!-- variant 2: grid (5 side-by-side cards, all windows visible at once) -->
  <%= render(Channel::WindowSummariesGridComponent.new(channels: @channels)) %>

  <%# Audience demographics variant gallery (2026-05-19).

      Two variants of the age × gender breakdown render here so the
      user can pick which lands as the canonical surface. After the
      user picks one, the other component + its render gets removed
      in a follow-up dispatch.

      Aggregation across selected channels = view-count-weighted mean
      of each channel's male / female × 7-age-bucket percentages.
      Components live in `app/components/channels/demographics_*_
      component.{rb,html.erb}`. Mock data lives in
      `Channel::DemographicsMock` (sibling to `Channel::MockData` to
      avoid the parallel-edit collision risk on `mock_data.rb` this
      slice). %>

  <hr class="hairline">

  <!-- variant 1: pyramid (two-sided population pyramid; male left, female right, age buckets vertical, shared center axis) -->
  <%= render(Channel::DemographicsPyramidComponent.new(channels: @channels)) %>

  <hr class="hairline">

  <!-- variant 2: grouped (side-by-side horizontal bars, one row per age bucket, male above + female below) -->
  <%= render(Channel::DemographicsGroupedComponent.new(channels: @channels)) %>

  <%# Audience geography variant gallery (2026-05-19).

      Three variants of the country viewership breakdown render here so
      the user can pick the visual treatment. After the user picks one,
      the other two components + their renders get removed in a follow-
      up dispatch.

      Aggregation across selected channels = sum of per-country
      `:views` from each channel's `:geography` array. Components live
      in `app/components/channels/geography_*_component.{rb,html.erb}`. %>

  <hr class="hairline">

  <!-- variant 1: ranked list with percentage bars (top-10, flag + code + name + bar + %) -->
  <%= render(Channel::GeographyListComponent.new(channels: @channels)) %>

  <!-- variant 2: horizontal bar chart (top-8, country name + bar scaled to max + compact view count) -->
  <%= render(Channel::GeographyBarComponent.new(channels: @channels)) %>

  <!-- variant 3: squarified treemap (top-10 + "Other", proportional rectangles + legend grid) -->
  <%= render(Channel::GeographyTreemapComponent.new(channels: @channels)) %>

  <%# Traffic sources variant gallery (2026-05-19).

      Two variants of the traffic-sources breakdown render here so the
      user can pick which lands as the canonical surface. After the
      user picks one, the other component + its render gets removed
      in a follow-up dispatch.

      Aggregation across selected channels = per-bucket view-weighted
      mean of each channel's source percentages, renormalized to 100;
      per-term search views summed across channels, sorted desc, top
      10. Components live in `app/components/channels/traffic_sources_
      *_component.{rb,html.erb}`. %>

  <hr class="hairline">

  <!-- variant 1: ranked list with horizontal bars + top-search-terms sub-section (compact, single column) -->
  <%= render(Channel::TrafficSourcesListComponent.new(channels: @channels)) %>

  <hr class="hairline">

  <!-- variant 2: split / side-by-side (left=sources, right=top search terms) -->
  <%= render(Channel::TrafficSourcesSplitComponent.new(channels: @channels)) %>

  <%# Viewer-time heatmap variant gallery (2026-05-19).

      "When your viewers are on YouTube" — two visual treatments
      of the day × hour activity matrix render here so the user can
      pick which lands as the canonical surface. After the pick the
      other component + its render gets removed in a follow-up
      dispatch.

      Aggregation across selected channels = per-cell sum of each
      channel's `:viewer_time_heatmap` (7 days × 24 hours). When the
      user has unchecked every channel (`@channels.empty?`), both
      variants receive an empty hash and render the empty-state
      grid / sparkline skeleton (zeros). %>

  <hr class="hairline">

  <% heatmap_data = Channel::MockData::DAYS_OF_WEEK if defined?(Channel::MockData::DAYS_OF_WEEK) %>
  <% heatmap_days = %w[Mon Tue Wed Thu Fri Sat Sun] %>
  <% aggregated_heatmap = heatmap_days.each_with_object({}) do |day, acc|
       summed = Array.new(24, 0)
       @channels.each do |c|
         values = Array(c[:viewer_time_heatmap]&.dig(day))
         24.times { |i| summed[i] += values[i].to_i }
       end
       acc[day] = summed
     end %>

  <div class="channels-heatmap-section">
    <h3 style="font-size: 13px;
               font-weight: 700;
               margin: 8px 0 6px;">
      when your viewers are on YouTube
    </h3>

    <!-- variant 1: color-intensity grid (7 rows × 24 cells, opacity ramp on --color-link) -->
    <%= render(Channel::HeatmapGridComponent.new(heatmap: aggregated_heatmap)) %>
  </div>

  <hr class="hairline">

  <div class="channels-heatmap-section">
    <h3 style="font-size: 13px;
               font-weight: 700;
               margin: 8px 0 6px;">
      when your viewers are on YouTube
    </h3>

    <!-- variant 2: stacked sparklines (7 days, each its own 360×32 SVG line+area chart) -->
    <%= render(Channel::HeatmapSparklineComponent.new(heatmap: aggregated_heatmap)) %>
  </div>
</section>
